# supermux deploy configuration — copy to `.env` and fill in your values.
# `scripts/deploy.sh` sources `.env` automatically if it exists. `.env` is
# gitignored; this file (`.env.example`) is committed as documentation.
#
# QUICKSTART: copy this file to `.env`, set SUPERMUX_DEPLOY_HOST, run
# `scripts/deploy.sh`. Everything else has sensible defaults — the service
# user is auto-created, ReadWritePaths defaults to a sane multi-project set,
# and Tailscale exposure is auto-detected from whether `tailscaled` is up.

# SSH target to deploy to (hostname or user@host). REQUIRED — no default.
SUPERMUX_DEPLOY_HOST=my-host

# NON-ROOT BY DEFAULT — even from a root SSH session. The account you DEPLOY
# WITH (your SSH login, often root on a fresh VPS) is NOT the account the
# service RUNS AS. Deploying over a root SSH session is fine and expected: root
# provisions (creates the service user, installs the unit). But the SERVICE runs
# as this unprivileged user, always, unless you explicitly force
# SUPERMUX_ALLOW_ROOT=1 (a loud, last-resort escape hatch — see below).
#
# Unix account on the host that owns the data dir and runs the service.
# If left as the default ("supermux") and the user doesn't yet exist on the
# host, `deploy.sh` auto-creates it for you, fully set up (`useradd -m -s
# /bin/bash supermux` + ownership of its home, data dir, and project dirs). If
# you pick a non-default user, you must create it yourself first — `deploy.sh`
# will refuse rather than silently create an unexpected account.
# SUPERMUX_SERVICE_USER=root is refused unless SUPERMUX_ALLOW_ROOT=1 is also set.
SUPERMUX_SERVICE_USER=supermux

# LAST RESORT — run the SERVICE as root. This is NOT just a hardening knob; it
# is a security + functionality trade-off you should avoid:
#   - the systemd sandbox is largely given up (ProtectHome=false,
#     ReadWritePaths=/root) — an auth-token leak or path-jail escape becomes
#     root-equivalent on the host;
#   - Claude Code REFUSES `--dangerously-skip-permissions` as uid 0, so your
#     agents may not run at all.
# Recommended instead: keep the default 'supermux' (root still runs the deploy;
# only the service drops to the unprivileged user). Default: 0. Set to 1 only if
# you have a hard requirement and accept the downsides (you'll see a loud
# warning at deploy time).
# SUPERMUX_ALLOW_ROOT=0

# Where your agents do their work — the project directories the service user
# must be able to read+write (clone repos, edit files, run builds). Colon-
# separated. Default: <user-home>/projects (e.g. /home/supermux/projects), which
# the service user already owns → zero permission fuss. Point elsewhere and
# deploy.sh wires it up for you: dirs UNDER the user's home just work; dirs
# OUTSIDE it (e.g. /opt/projects, /srv/work) are created and `chown -R`'d to the
# service user, and added to the systemd ReadWritePaths so the sandbox permits
# the writes. Example:
# SUPERMUX_PROJECT_DIRS=/opt/projects:/srv/work

# Service-user Claude login — fast path. supermux uses your Claude SUBSCRIPTION
# (OAuth), NEVER an API key / ANTHROPIC_API_KEY / API billing. The service user
# must be logged in (`sudo -u supermux -i claude` then `/login`). If the account
# you deploy AS already has a valid Claude login, deploy.sh can copy it to the
# service user (reusing your subscription). Values:
#   ask  (default) — prompt y/n interactively when creds are missing;
#   1              — copy the deployer's login without prompting (non-interactive
#                    fast path);
#   0              — never copy; just print the manual /login instructions.
# deploy.sh ALWAYS verifies the service user has usable Claude creds before
# declaring success, and warns loudly (with the exact /login command) if not.
# SUPERMUX_COPY_CLAUDE_CREDS=ask

# Data directory on the host (holds the SQLite DB, auth token, config.toml,
# uploads). DELIBERATELY SEPARATE from SUPERMUX_USER_HOME: keeping the data
# dir scoped to its own tree means a `rm -rf $SUPERMUX_DATA_DIR` does not
# nuke the user's shell history or agent caches, and dotfiles from spawned
# shells/agents do not pollute the data dir. Default derives from
# SUPERMUX_SERVICE_USER: <user-home>/.supermux for non-root, /root/.supermux
# for root.
# SUPERMUX_DATA_DIR=/home/supermux/.supermux

# Extra writable roots for the systemd ReadWritePaths= directive — colon
# separated. When unset, `deploy.sh` derives a sane default: the data dir, the
# service user's home directory, the project dirs (SUPERMUX_PROJECT_DIRS, see
# above), and /opt/projects (only if that dir exists on the host). That covers
# single-user, single-project, and the common multi-project layout out of the
# box. If you DO set this explicitly, deploy.sh still appends your project dirs
# (agents must be able to write there). Override only if you need something
# else, e.g.:
# SUPERMUX_READ_WRITE_PATHS=/home/supermux:/opt/projects:/srv/scratch

# Loopback port the server binds to on the host (plain HTTP).
# SUPERMUX_INTERNAL_PORT=8824

# Public HTTPS port — used only when Tailscale is enabled (see below).
# Default 443 gives you the clean URL `https://<host>.<tailnet>.ts.net/` (no
# port suffix). Tailscale terminates TLS natively on 443 inside the tailnet —
# tip: rename the host with `sudo tailscale set --hostname=supermux` so the
# URL reads `https://supermux.<your-tailnet>.ts.net/`. Set to another port
# (e.g. 8443) only if 443 is already taken by another tailscale-serve binding.
# SUPERMUX_PUBLIC_PORT=443

# Expose the service via `tailscale serve`. When unset, `deploy.sh`
# auto-detects: if the host has `tailscale` installed AND `tailscaled` is
# running, it defaults to 1 (expose). Otherwise it defaults to 0 (skip — you
# front the loopback port with your own reverse proxy: nginx, Caddy, …).
# Override with 0 or 1 to force either behaviour.
# SUPERMUX_USE_TAILSCALE=1

# Build/source directory on the host (a pinned git archive is unpacked here).
# SUPERMUX_REMOTE_DIR=/opt/supermux

# Git ref to deploy. The working tree must be clean; defaults to HEAD.
# SUPERMUX_DEPLOY_REF=HEAD

# ─── Advanced / opt-in ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Service user's login HOME on the host. The systemd unit's WorkingDirectory
# and $HOME both point here so spawned shells/agents (claude, codex, tmux
# children) resolve their dotfiles (.bash_history, .claude/, .claude.json,
# .cache/, .local/, …) in the conventional place — NOT inside the supermux
# data dir. By default deploy.sh derives this from SUPERMUX_SERVICE_USER:
# `/root` for root, `getent passwd <user>` if the account exists locally,
# `/home/<user>` otherwise. Set this explicitly only for non-standard layouts
# (e.g. accounts homed under /srv or /var/lib).
# SUPERMUX_USER_HOME=/home/supermux

# Opt in to automatic toolchain installation on the host. When the host is
# missing `bun` or `cargo` and this is set to 1, `deploy.sh` installs them
# under the service user's home using the official installers (bun pinned to
# your local bun version; rustup with --default-toolchain stable). Without
# this opt-in, a missing toolchain is a hard error with manual-install
# instructions. Default: 0.
# SUPERMUX_INSTALL_TOOLCHAINS=0

# Install a cargo-guard wrapper that refuses `cargo --release` from ad-hoc
# agent invocations (unless SUPERMUX_RELEASE_OK=1 is set, which the legit
# build.sh / deploy-self.sh paths do).
# AUTO-ON when the host has ≤8 GiB RAM (the wedge regime — release builds
# peak ~2 GB/rustc and can OOM-thrash small boxes); OFF on bigger hosts.
# Set explicitly to override: 0 disables it everywhere, 1 enables it everywhere.
# SUPERMUX_INSTALL_CARGO_GUARD=0

# Soft memory throttle for the supermux cgroup (server + tmux + agents + their
# children). Maps to the systemd unit's MemoryHigh= directive. SOFT means the
# kernel reclaims aggressively past the threshold but NEVER OOM-kills — so an
# over-tight value just slows things down, it doesn't break the service. Pairs
# with OOMScoreAdjust=200 (already in the unit), which biases the OOM-killer
# toward this cgroup if the host as a whole still tips into OOM.
# Default: `infinity` = NO CAP. So the rendered unit is identical to the
# previous version for every existing operator — opt in to throttle.
# Suggested values:
#   `6G`   on an 8 GiB host  (leaves ~2 GiB for kernel + ssh + other services)
#   `12G`  on a 16 GiB host
#   `infinity` (default) — no cap
# SUPERMUX_MEMORY_HIGH=infinity

# Strict memory hardening (W^X) — OFF by default so agents can build. supermux
# hosts CODING agents, and they MUST be able to run build tools: npm, React,
# Vite, Next, Jest, esbuild — anything that uses V8 JIT or WebAssembly. This
# knob maps to the systemd unit's MemoryDenyWriteExecute directive:
#   0 (DEFAULT, dev-friendly) → MemoryDenyWriteExecute=no. Agent build tools
#     work. With W^X on, the kernel rejects the JIT's mprotect(PROT_EXEC)
#     (ENOMEM), so those builds fail for the service AND every agent child
#     (inherited via NoNewPrivileges) — which defeats the product's core use.
#   1 (strict) → MemoryDenyWriteExecute=yes. Classic W^X for the
#     security-paranoid; JS/WASM builds WILL fail. Only set this if you do NOT
#     need agents to run build tools.
# This is the ONLY directive that changes between modes. ALL other sandboxing
# stays ON either way and is the real jail: non-root user, ProtectSystem=strict,
# the ReadWritePaths jail, PrivateTmp, RestrictAddressFamilies, dropped
# capabilities, NoNewPrivileges, and the @system-service syscall filter.
# SUPERMUX_HARDENED=0
